title.narrative: OUTPUT 2.1: INFANT & YOUNG CHILD FEEDING

description.narrative: Output 2.1: Infant and young child feeding practices improved with at least 40% of children below two years with acceptable diet, with special emphasis on most marginalised and vulnerable families, which contributes to Infant And Young Child Feeding, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 2: By 2019, the nutritional status of children under five years, adolescent girls, and women of child bearing age improved with special focus on the reduction of chronic malnutrition in children below2 years.

description.narrative: By October 2019, 53% of children aged 6–8 months were introduced timely to complementary feeding against the annual target of 52%; about half (51 per cent) of all children 0-5 months are exclusively fed with breastmilk; 23% of children aged 6-23 months receive food that meets minimum dietary diversity while only 11% of them meet minimum acceptable diet | Status:Met | As-of Date:26/12/2019
